<subSubSection id="C36D6519EF5CA421FF5FFA7BFBADFA2F" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="255" pageId="1" pageNumber="254" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BC83692EF5CA422FF5FFA7BFC2FF9CB" blockId="1.[178,1085,1453,1562]" pageId="1" pageNumber="254">
D e s c r i p t i o n: Body length 3.5-4.0 mm. Habitus as in 
<figureCitation id="134C2A17EF5CA422FCACFA7BFC06FA12" box="[833,897,1453,1475]" captionStart="Figs 1-14" captionStartId="3.[178,218,1445,1465]" captionTargetBox="[190,1085,208,1415]" captionTargetId="figure-114@3.[178,1085,208,1418]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs 1-14: Leptusa gibbera nov.sp.: (1) female habitus; (2) male forebody; (3) female forebody; (4) median dorsal portion of head; (5) antenna; (6) median portion of pronotum; (7) male abdominal tergites III-VII; (8) male tergite VIII; (9) male sternite VIII; (10) median lobe of aedeagus in lateral view; (11) apical lobe of paramere; (12) female tergite VIII; (13) female sternite VIII; (14) spermatheca. Scale bars: 1: 1.0 mm; 2-3, 5, 7: 0.5 mm; 8-10, 12-13: 0.2 mm; 4, 6, 11, 14: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5324198" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5324198/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="254">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
. Coloration: head dark-brown to blackish-brown; pronotum and elytra brown to dark-brown; abdomen brown, with segment VI and anterior half of segment VII infuscate; legs and antennae reddish to reddish brown, usually with antennomeres I-III somewhat paler.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC83692EF5CA421FF5FF9FCFB94FE52" blockId="1.[178,1084,1578,1600]" lastBlockId="2.[178,1086,219,387]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="255" pageId="1" pageNumber="254">
Head (
<figureCitation id="134C2A17EF5CA422FF1BF9FCFECAF991" box="[246,333,1578,1600]" captionStart="Figs 1-14" captionStartId="3.[178,218,1445,1465]" captionTargetBox="[190,1085,208,1415]" captionTargetId="figure-114@3.[178,1085,208,1418]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs 1-14: Leptusa gibbera nov.sp.: (1) female habitus; (2) male forebody; (3) female forebody; (4) median dorsal portion of head; (5) antenna; (6) median portion of pronotum; (7) male abdominal tergites III-VII; (8) male tergite VIII; (9) male sternite VIII; (10) median lobe of aedeagus in lateral view; (11) apical lobe of paramere; (12) female tergite VIII; (13) female sternite VIII; (14) spermatheca. Scale bars: 1: 1.0 mm; 2-3, 5, 7: 0.5 mm; 8-10, 12-13: 0.2 mm; 4, 6, 11, 14: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5324198" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5324198/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="254">Figs 2-3</figureCitation>
) approximately as long as wide or weakly oblong; punctation dense and shallow, somewhat indistinct in the pronounced microsculpture (
<figureCitation id="134C2A17EF5FA421FCB8FF0DFC11FF20" box="[853,918,219,241]" captionStart="Figs 1-14" captionStartId="3.[178,218,1445,1465]" captionTargetBox="[190,1085,208,1415]" captionTargetId="figure-114@3.[178,1085,208,1418]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs 1-14: Leptusa gibbera nov.sp.: (1) female habitus; (2) male forebody; (3) female forebody; (4) median dorsal portion of head; (5) antenna; (6) median portion of pronotum; (7) male abdominal tergites III-VII; (8) male tergite VIII; (9) male sternite VIII; (10) median lobe of aedeagus in lateral view; (11) apical lobe of paramere; (12) female tergite VIII; (13) female sternite VIII; (14) spermatheca. Scale bars: 1: 1.0 mm; 2-3, 5, 7: 0.5 mm; 8-10, 12-13: 0.2 mm; 4, 6, 11, 14: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5324198" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5324198/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="255">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
); dorsal surface almost matt; eyes weakly convex, not distinctly projecting from lateral contours of head, slightly shorter than postocular portion in dorsal view. Antenna rather slender (
<figureCitation id="134C2A17EF5FA421FC02FEC3FBB7FEFA" box="[1007,1072,277,299]" captionStart="Figs 1-14" captionStartId="3.[178,218,1445,1465]" captionTargetBox="[190,1085,208,1415]" captionTargetId="figure-114@3.[178,1085,208,1418]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs 1-14: Leptusa gibbera nov.sp.: (1) female habitus; (2) male forebody; (3) female forebody; (4) median dorsal portion of head; (5) antenna; (6) median portion of pronotum; (7) male abdominal tergites III-VII; (8) male tergite VIII; (9) male sternite VIII; (10) median lobe of aedeagus in lateral view; (11) apical lobe of paramere; (12) female tergite VIII; (13) female sternite VIII; (14) spermatheca. Scale bars: 1: 1.0 mm; 2-3, 5, 7: 0.5 mm; 8-10, 12-13: 0.2 mm; 4, 6, 11, 14: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5324198" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5324198/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="255">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
), approximately 1.0 mm long; antennomeres I-III distinctly oblong and of subequal length; IV weakly oblong; V approximately as wide as long; X barely 1.5 times as wide as long. Maxillary palpi slender; preapical palpomere approximately 4 times as long as broad.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC83692EF5FA421FF5FFE45FE5FFDD1" blockId="2.[178,1086,402,512]" pageId="2" pageNumber="255">
Pronotum (
<figureCitation id="134C2A17EF5FA421FEC9FE44FEFDFE79" box="[292,378,402,424]" captionStart="Figs 1-14" captionStartId="3.[178,218,1445,1465]" captionTargetBox="[190,1085,208,1415]" captionTargetId="figure-114@3.[178,1085,208,1418]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs 1-14: Leptusa gibbera nov.sp.: (1) female habitus; (2) male forebody; (3) female forebody; (4) median dorsal portion of head; (5) antenna; (6) median portion of pronotum; (7) male abdominal tergites III-VII; (8) male tergite VIII; (9) male sternite VIII; (10) median lobe of aedeagus in lateral view; (11) apical lobe of paramere; (12) female tergite VIII; (13) female sternite VIII; (14) spermatheca. Scale bars: 1: 1.0 mm; 2-3, 5, 7: 0.5 mm; 8-10, 12-13: 0.2 mm; 4, 6, 11, 14: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5324198" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5324198/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="255">Figs 2-3</figureCitation>
) approximately 1.25-1.30 times as wide as long and 1.30-1.35 times as wide as head; maximal width in, or slightly before middle; posterior angles marked; punctation dense, fine, and shallow, not very evident in the pronounced microsculpture (
<figureCitation id="134C2A17EF5FA421FF57FE3CFF7FFDD1" box="[186,248,490,512]" captionStart="Figs 1-14" captionStartId="3.[178,218,1445,1465]" captionTargetBox="[190,1085,208,1415]" captionTargetId="figure-114@3.[178,1085,208,1418]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs 1-14: Leptusa gibbera nov.sp.: (1) female habitus; (2) male forebody; (3) female forebody; (4) median dorsal portion of head; (5) antenna; (6) median portion of pronotum; (7) male abdominal tergites III-VII; (8) male tergite VIII; (9) male sternite VIII; (10) median lobe of aedeagus in lateral view; (11) apical lobe of paramere; (12) female tergite VIII; (13) female sternite VIII; (14) spermatheca. Scale bars: 1: 1.0 mm; 2-3, 5, 7: 0.5 mm; 8-10, 12-13: 0.2 mm; 4, 6, 11, 14: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5324198" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5324198/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="255">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
); surface almost matt.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC83692EF5FA421FF5FFDD9FF55FD66" blockId="2.[178,1086,527,695]" pageId="2" pageNumber="255">
Elytra (
<figureCitation id="134C2A17EF5FA421FF13FDD9FED3FDF4" box="[254,340,527,549]" captionStart="Figs 1-14" captionStartId="3.[178,218,1445,1465]" captionTargetBox="[190,1085,208,1415]" captionTargetId="figure-114@3.[178,1085,208,1418]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs 1-14: Leptusa gibbera nov.sp.: (1) female habitus; (2) male forebody; (3) female forebody; (4) median dorsal portion of head; (5) antenna; (6) median portion of pronotum; (7) male abdominal tergites III-VII; (8) male tergite VIII; (9) male sternite VIII; (10) median lobe of aedeagus in lateral view; (11) apical lobe of paramere; (12) female tergite VIII; (13) female sternite VIII; (14) spermatheca. Scale bars: 1: 1.0 mm; 2-3, 5, 7: 0.5 mm; 8-10, 12-13: 0.2 mm; 4, 6, 11, 14: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5324198" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5324198/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="255">Figs 2-3</figureCitation>
) sexually dimorphic, 0.85-0.95 times as long as pronotum, laterally with rather pronounced and extensive oblong impression; posterior margin distinctly sinuate near postero-lateral angles; punctation much more pronounced than that of head and pronotum; interstices with shallow microsculpture and subdued shine. Hind wings reduced. Legs slender; metatarsomere I slightly longer than the combined length of II and III.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC83692EF5FA421FF5FFD11FE50FCE4" blockId="2.[178,1086,711,821]" pageId="2" pageNumber="255">
Abdomen subparallel, approximately as wide as elytra; tergites III-V with deep and coarsely punctate anterior impressions (
<figureCitation id="134C2A17EF5FA421FDABFD32FD02FD2B" box="[582,645,740,762]" captionStart="Figs 1-14" captionStartId="3.[178,218,1445,1465]" captionTargetBox="[190,1085,208,1415]" captionTargetId="figure-114@3.[178,1085,208,1418]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs 1-14: Leptusa gibbera nov.sp.: (1) female habitus; (2) male forebody; (3) female forebody; (4) median dorsal portion of head; (5) antenna; (6) median portion of pronotum; (7) male abdominal tergites III-VII; (8) male tergite VIII; (9) male sternite VIII; (10) median lobe of aedeagus in lateral view; (11) apical lobe of paramere; (12) female tergite VIII; (13) female sternite VIII; (14) spermatheca. Scale bars: 1: 1.0 mm; 2-3, 5, 7: 0.5 mm; 8-10, 12-13: 0.2 mm; 4, 6, 11, 14: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5324198" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5324198/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="255">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
); punctation distinct, dense on anterior and sparser on posterior tergites; posterior margin of tergite VII with palisade fringe; tergite VII with sexual dimorphism.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC83692EF5FA421FF2AFC93FD3BFBF6" blockId="2.[178,1086,836,1063]" pageId="2" pageNumber="255">
: elytra with pronounced protuberance on either side of suture (
<figureCitation id="134C2A17EF5FA421FCA6FC92FC0DFC8B" box="[843,906,836,858]" captionStart="Figs 1-14" captionStartId="3.[178,218,1445,1465]" captionTargetBox="[190,1085,208,1415]" captionTargetId="figure-114@3.[178,1085,208,1418]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs 1-14: Leptusa gibbera nov.sp.: (1) female habitus; (2) male forebody; (3) female forebody; (4) median dorsal portion of head; (5) antenna; (6) median portion of pronotum; (7) male abdominal tergites III-VII; (8) male tergite VIII; (9) male sternite VIII; (10) median lobe of aedeagus in lateral view; (11) apical lobe of paramere; (12) female tergite VIII; (13) female sternite VIII; (14) spermatheca. Scale bars: 1: 1.0 mm; 2-3, 5, 7: 0.5 mm; 8-10, 12-13: 0.2 mm; 4, 6, 11, 14: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5324198" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5324198/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="255">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
); tergite VII with smooth and distinctly elevated long median carina (
<figureCitation id="134C2A17EF5FA421FD21FCB7FC8AFCA6" box="[716,781,865,887]" captionStart="Figs 1-14" captionStartId="3.[178,218,1445,1465]" captionTargetBox="[190,1085,208,1415]" captionTargetId="figure-114@3.[178,1085,208,1418]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs 1-14: Leptusa gibbera nov.sp.: (1) female habitus; (2) male forebody; (3) female forebody; (4) median dorsal portion of head; (5) antenna; (6) median portion of pronotum; (7) male abdominal tergites III-VII; (8) male tergite VIII; (9) male sternite VIII; (10) median lobe of aedeagus in lateral view; (11) apical lobe of paramere; (12) female tergite VIII; (13) female sternite VIII; (14) spermatheca. Scale bars: 1: 1.0 mm; 2-3, 5, 7: 0.5 mm; 8-10, 12-13: 0.2 mm; 4, 6, 11, 14: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5324198" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5324198/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="255">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
); posterior margin of sternite VII broadly and weakly concave, on either side of this concavity with two very long marginal setae; tergite VIII with short and weakly pronounced median carina, posterior margin weakly concave in the middle (
<figureCitation id="134C2A17EF5FA421FDA3FC6FFD08FC1E" box="[590,655,953,975]" captionStart="Figs 1-14" captionStartId="3.[178,218,1445,1465]" captionTargetBox="[190,1085,208,1415]" captionTargetId="figure-114@3.[178,1085,208,1418]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs 1-14: Leptusa gibbera nov.sp.: (1) female habitus; (2) male forebody; (3) female forebody; (4) median dorsal portion of head; (5) antenna; (6) median portion of pronotum; (7) male abdominal tergites III-VII; (8) male tergite VIII; (9) male sternite VIII; (10) median lobe of aedeagus in lateral view; (11) apical lobe of paramere; (12) female tergite VIII; (13) female sternite VIII; (14) spermatheca. Scale bars: 1: 1.0 mm; 2-3, 5, 7: 0.5 mm; 8-10, 12-13: 0.2 mm; 4, 6, 11, 14: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5324198" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5324198/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="255">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
); sternite VIII oblong, much longer than tergite VIII, posterior margin obtusely produced in the middle (
<figureCitation id="134C2A17EF5FA421FC93FC00FC42FC3D" box="[894,965,982,1004]" captionStart="Figs 1-14" captionStartId="3.[178,218,1445,1465]" captionTargetBox="[190,1085,208,1415]" captionTargetId="figure-114@3.[178,1085,208,1418]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs 1-14: Leptusa gibbera nov.sp.: (1) female habitus; (2) male forebody; (3) female forebody; (4) median dorsal portion of head; (5) antenna; (6) median portion of pronotum; (7) male abdominal tergites III-VII; (8) male tergite VIII; (9) male sternite VIII; (10) median lobe of aedeagus in lateral view; (11) apical lobe of paramere; (12) female tergite VIII; (13) female sternite VIII; (14) spermatheca. Scale bars: 1: 1.0 mm; 2-3, 5, 7: 0.5 mm; 8-10, 12-13: 0.2 mm; 4, 6, 11, 14: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5324198" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5324198/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="255">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
); aedeagus 
<quantity id="4C8F9B77EF5FA421FF5FFC22FE8BFBD8" box="[178,268,1012,1034]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.8" pageId="2" pageNumber="255" unit="mm" value="0.68">0.68 mm</quantity>
long, with long and slender ventral process and with long internal structures (
<figureCitation id="134C2A17EF5FA421FF57FBC7FE82FBF6" box="[186,261,1041,1063]" captionStart="Figs 1-14" captionStartId="3.[178,218,1445,1465]" captionTargetBox="[190,1085,208,1415]" captionTargetId="figure-114@3.[178,1085,208,1418]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs 1-14: Leptusa gibbera nov.sp.: (1) female habitus; (2) male forebody; (3) female forebody; (4) median dorsal portion of head; (5) antenna; (6) median portion of pronotum; (7) male abdominal tergites III-VII; (8) male tergite VIII; (9) male sternite VIII; (10) median lobe of aedeagus in lateral view; (11) apical lobe of paramere; (12) female tergite VIII; (13) female sternite VIII; (14) spermatheca. Scale bars: 1: 1.0 mm; 2-3, 5, 7: 0.5 mm; 8-10, 12-13: 0.2 mm; 4, 6, 11, 14: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5324198" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5324198/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="255">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
); apical lobe of paramere slender (
<figureCitation id="134C2A17EF5FA421FD89FBC7FD29FBF6" box="[612,686,1041,1063]" captionStart="Figs 1-14" captionStartId="3.[178,218,1445,1465]" captionTargetBox="[190,1085,208,1415]" captionTargetId="figure-114@3.[178,1085,208,1418]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs 1-14: Leptusa gibbera nov.sp.: (1) female habitus; (2) male forebody; (3) female forebody; (4) median dorsal portion of head; (5) antenna; (6) median portion of pronotum; (7) male abdominal tergites III-VII; (8) male tergite VIII; (9) male sternite VIII; (10) median lobe of aedeagus in lateral view; (11) apical lobe of paramere; (12) female tergite VIII; (13) female sternite VIII; (14) spermatheca. Scale bars: 1: 1.0 mm; 2-3, 5, 7: 0.5 mm; 8-10, 12-13: 0.2 mm; 4, 6, 11, 14: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5324198" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5324198/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="255">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC83692EF5FA421FF2AFBE1FE6DFB56" blockId="2.[178,1086,1078,1159]" pageId="2" pageNumber="255">
: elytra without protuberances (
<figureCitation id="134C2A17EF5FA421FDFBFBE0FDDFFB9D" box="[534,600,1078,1100]" captionStart="Figs 1-14" captionStartId="3.[178,218,1445,1465]" captionTargetBox="[190,1085,208,1415]" captionTargetId="figure-114@3.[178,1085,208,1418]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs 1-14: Leptusa gibbera nov.sp.: (1) female habitus; (2) male forebody; (3) female forebody; (4) median dorsal portion of head; (5) antenna; (6) median portion of pronotum; (7) male abdominal tergites III-VII; (8) male tergite VIII; (9) male sternite VIII; (10) median lobe of aedeagus in lateral view; (11) apical lobe of paramere; (12) female tergite VIII; (13) female sternite VIII; (14) spermatheca. Scale bars: 1: 1.0 mm; 2-3, 5, 7: 0.5 mm; 8-10, 12-13: 0.2 mm; 4, 6, 11, 14: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5324198" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5324198/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="255">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
); posterior margin of tergite VIII indistinctly concave in the middle (
<figureCitation id="134C2A17EF5FA421FE4BFB82FE73FBBB" box="[422,500,1108,1130]" captionStart="Figs 1-14" captionStartId="3.[178,218,1445,1465]" captionTargetBox="[190,1085,208,1415]" captionTargetId="figure-114@3.[178,1085,208,1418]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs 1-14: Leptusa gibbera nov.sp.: (1) female habitus; (2) male forebody; (3) female forebody; (4) median dorsal portion of head; (5) antenna; (6) median portion of pronotum; (7) male abdominal tergites III-VII; (8) male tergite VIII; (9) male sternite VIII; (10) median lobe of aedeagus in lateral view; (11) apical lobe of paramere; (12) female tergite VIII; (13) female sternite VIII; (14) spermatheca. Scale bars: 1: 1.0 mm; 2-3, 5, 7: 0.5 mm; 8-10, 12-13: 0.2 mm; 4, 6, 11, 14: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5324198" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5324198/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="255">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
); posterior margin of sternite VIII strongly convex (
<figureCitation id="134C2A17EF5FA421FBF9FB82FF49FB56" captionStart="Figs 1-14" captionStartId="3.[178,218,1445,1465]" captionTargetBox="[190,1085,208,1415]" captionTargetId="figure-114@3.[178,1085,208,1418]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs 1-14: Leptusa gibbera nov.sp.: (1) female habitus; (2) male forebody; (3) female forebody; (4) median dorsal portion of head; (5) antenna; (6) median portion of pronotum; (7) male abdominal tergites III-VII; (8) male tergite VIII; (9) male sternite VIII; (10) median lobe of aedeagus in lateral view; (11) apical lobe of paramere; (12) female tergite VIII; (13) female sternite VIII; (14) spermatheca. Scale bars: 1: 1.0 mm; 2-3, 5, 7: 0.5 mm; 8-10, 12-13: 0.2 mm; 4, 6, 11, 14: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5324198" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5324198/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="255">Fig. 13</figureCitation>
); spermatheca as in 
<figureCitation id="134C2A17EF5FA421FE76FBA7FE6DFB56" box="[411,490,1137,1159]" captionStart="Figs 1-14" captionStartId="3.[178,218,1445,1465]" captionTargetBox="[190,1085,208,1415]" captionTargetId="figure-114@3.[178,1085,208,1418]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs 1-14: Leptusa gibbera nov.sp.: (1) female habitus; (2) male forebody; (3) female forebody; (4) median dorsal portion of head; (5) antenna; (6) median portion of pronotum; (7) male abdominal tergites III-VII; (8) male tergite VIII; (9) male sternite VIII; (10) median lobe of aedeagus in lateral view; (11) apical lobe of paramere; (12) female tergite VIII; (13) female sternite VIII; (14) spermatheca. Scale bars: 1: 1.0 mm; 2-3, 5, 7: 0.5 mm; 8-10, 12-13: 0.2 mm; 4, 6, 11, 14: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5324198" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5324198/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="255">Fig. 14.</figureCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC83692EF5FA421FF5FFB41FD0DFB18" blockId="2.[178,1085,1174,1225]" pageId="2" pageNumber="255">E t y m o l o g y: The specific epithet is a Latin adjective (with protuberances) and alludes to the modifications of the male elytra.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC83692EF5FA421FF5FFB0FFDF5FA4F" blockId="2.[178,1086,1241,1438]" pageId="2" pageNumber="255">
C o m p a r a t i v e n o t e s: Based on the conspicuous derived morphology of the aedeagus, 
<taxonomicName id="4C774D11EF5FA421FEF3FB21FE0CFADD" authorityName="Assing" authorityYear="2011" box="[286,395,1270,1292]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Leptusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="255" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gibbera">
<emphasis id="B903EA80EF5FA421FEF3FB21FE0CFADD" box="[286,395,1270,1292]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="255">L. gibbera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is closely related to 
<taxonomicName id="4C774D11EF5FA421FD80FB21FC4FFADD" authority="(HOCHHUTH 1849)" baseAuthorityName="HOCHHUTH" baseAuthorityYear="1849" box="[621,968,1270,1292]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Leptusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="255" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="laeviuscula">
<emphasis id="B903EA80EF5FA421FD80FB21FD79FADD" box="[621,766,1270,1292]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="255">L. laeviuscula</emphasis>
(HOCHHUTH 1849)
</taxonomicName>
and to the syntopic 
<taxonomicName id="4C774D11EF5FA421FEE3FAC2FEF1FAF8" baseAuthorityName="HOCHHUTH" baseAuthorityYear="1849" box="[270,374,1300,1321]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Leptusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="255" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="venusta">
<emphasis id="B903EA80EF5FA421FEE3FAC2FEF1FAF8" box="[270,374,1300,1321]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="255">L. venusta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. It is distinguished from both of them by the shorter and more slender elytra (in 
<taxonomicName id="4C774D11EF5FA421FEFAFAE7FEF8FA97" baseAuthorityName="HOCHHUTH" baseAuthorityYear="1849" box="[279,383,1329,1350]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Leptusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="255" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="venusta">
<emphasis id="B903EA80EF5FA421FEFAFAE7FEF8FA97" box="[279,383,1329,1350]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="255">L. venusta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C774D11EF5FA421FE5FFAE7FDC7FA96" baseAuthorityName="HOCHHUTH" baseAuthorityYear="1849" box="[434,576,1329,1351]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Leptusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="255" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="laeviuscula">
<emphasis id="B903EA80EF5FA421FE5FFAE7FDC7FA96" box="[434,576,1329,1351]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="255">L. laeviuscula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
at least as long as the pronotum), the pronounced lateral impressions of the elytra, the pronounced protuberances on the male elytra, and particularly by the morphology of the aedeagus. For illustrations of the genitalia of 
<taxonomicName id="4C774D11EF5FA421FBC5FABAFF78FA4F" baseAuthorityName="HOCHHUTH" baseAuthorityYear="1849" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Leptusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="255" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="venusta">
<emphasis id="B903EA80EF5FA421FBC5FABAFF78FA4F" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="255">L. venusta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C774D11EF5FA421FEDDFA5FFE39FA4F" baseAuthorityName="HOCHHUTH" baseAuthorityYear="1849" box="[304,446,1416,1438]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Leptusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="255" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="laeviuscula">
<emphasis id="B903EA80EF5FA421FEDDFA5FFE39FA4F" box="[304,446,1416,1438]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="255">L. laeviuscula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
see 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE64B63EF5FA421FE06FA5FFDE8FA4F" author="PACE R" box="[491,623,1416,1438]" pageId="2" pageNumber="255" pagination="1 - 307" refId="ref5908" refString="PACE R. (1989): Monografia del genere Leptusa KRAATZ (Coleoptera Staphylinidae). - Memorie del Museo Civico di Storia Naturale di Verona (II ° Serie), Sezione Scienze della Vita (A: Biologica) 8: 1 - 307." type="journal article" year="1989">PACE (1989)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC83692EF5FA421FF5FFA78FBADFA2F" blockId="2.[178,1085,1454,1534]" pageId="2" pageNumber="255">
D i s t r i b u t i o n a n d n a t u r a l h i s t o r y: Thespecimenswerecollected near Mezmay, Krasnodarskiy Kray, Western Caucasus, at altitudes of 
<quantity id="4C8F9B77EF5FA421FC67FA1DFC7AFA30" box="[906,1021,1483,1505]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.75" metricValueMax="8.0" metricValueMin="7.5" pageId="2" pageNumber="255" unit="m" value="775.0" valueMax="800.0" valueMin="750.0">
750- 
<specimenCount id="9D71FD1BEF5FA421FC55FA1DFC7AFA30" box="[952,1021,1483,1505]" pageId="2" pageNumber="255" type="generic">800 m</specimenCount>
</quantity>
. They were sifted from deep leaf litter in mixed beech and fir forests (SMETANA pers. comm.).
</paragraph>
